# examples/tiny-linux-experiments/floppinux/hand-walk/Containerfile — reproduce
# Krzysztof Jankowski's environment so you can walk "FLOPPINUX (2025 edition)"
# BY HAND, step-by-step.
#
#   Upstream post : ../upstream-tutorial/  (byte-exact archive + provenance)
#   Canonical URL : https://krzysztofjankowski.com/floppinux/floppinux-2025.html
#   What it shows : a whole bootable Linux (kernel + BusyBox) on a single 1.44 MB
#                   floppy, cross-built with a musl toolchain and made bootable
#                   with syslinux.
#
# This is the HAND-WALK sandbox (TODO #3): an **Arch Linux** box (the author runs
# "Omarchy" = Arch; the post's commands are `pacman`) carrying the build deps, so
# you follow Jankowski's exact recipe by hand. The repo's automated counterpart is
# ../build-floppinux.sh (rootless; the same gate split applies — see below).
#
# ── TWO steps are author-only — flagged honestly ─────────────────────────────
# 1. **musl cross-toolchain (RUNBOOK §2).** The post `wget`s a prebuilt toolchain
#    from musl.cc and compiles with it. Fetching + executing a third-party
#    prebuilt toolchain is your machine's call to trust — and this repo's agent
#    runner blocks it (same posture as ../README.md's build note). So you run the
#    fetch + `make bzImage`/busybox compile.
# 2. **The floppy image (RUNBOOK §5).** `mknod` for /dev/console+/dev/null and
#    `mount -o loop` need real device access, which this build sandbox denies even
#    with --privileged. On your own host they work; here they're author-only.
#
# What IS verified here: the Arch environment builds and carries the build deps.
# On your host:
#   phase4-podman/lab-podman.sh build --tag floppinux-handwalk \
#       --context examples/tiny-linux-experiments/floppinux/hand-walk
#   podman run --rm -it --privileged floppinux-handwalk bash   # --privileged for §5
ARG BASE=docker.io/library/archlinux:latest
FROM ${BASE}

# ── The post's prerequisites (pacman).  Each maps to a step:
#   base-devel       → host gcc/make/etc. for the kernel kconfig + build machinery
#                      (the *cross* compile uses the musl.cc toolchain from §2)
#   ncurses bc flex bison → kernel + BusyBox `menuconfig` and build
#   cpio xz          → pack the initramfs (cpio -H newc | xz)
#   syslinux         → make the FAT floppy bootable
#   dosfstools       → mkdosfs (mkfs.fat) to format the 1.44 MB image
#   wget             → fetch the musl toolchain (§2) + the kernel/BusyBox sources
#   qemu-system-x86  → boot the finished floppy: qemu-system-i386 -fda
RUN pacman -Syu --noconfirm \
        base-devel ncurses bc flex bison \
        cpio xz syslinux dosfstools wget qemu-system-x86 \
 && pacman -Scc --noconfirm

WORKDIR /work
CMD ["bash"]
